"CORE_NARRATIVE: Traditional light field analysis fails in complex real-world scenes because low-resolution angular sampling (e.g., 9x9) causes severe aliasing of illumination, depth, and material signals, rendering spectral methods and standard EPI structures ineffective. By abandoning failed spectral analysis in favor of a physics-based three-layer angular decomposition and dual-branch routing mechanism, this work decouples these signals at the geometric level. This paradigm shift breaks the low-resolution sampling bottleneck, providing a reliable physical foundation for accurate depth estimation in non-Lambertian environments.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open with the critical failure of light field depth estimation on non-Lambertian surfaces in real-world scenarios, immediately pinpointing the root cause: the physical signal aliasing inherent in low-resolution (e.g., 9x9) discrete angular sampling.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Highlight that existing spectral (2D-DFT) and single-branch EPI methods hit an insurmountable \"physical resolution bottleneck\" under low sampling rates—evidenced by X-shaped EPI distortions rather than linear structures—necessitating a fundamental shift from frequency-domain analysis to physics-based geometric decomposition.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: Justify the three-layer decomposition model ($I = DC + linear + \\epsilon$) and dual-branch routing as direct mathematical and architectural counterparts to physically isolate ambient light, parallax, and material residuals, deliberately replacing failed spectral features with robust geometric angular features.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Design experiments to explicitly prove the efficacy of physical decoupling, showcasing the Random Forest classifier's high AUC (0.962), the large effect size of geometric features (Cohen's d = 0.983), and the dual-branch mechanism's success in drastically reducing MAE in non-Lambertian scenes compared to single-branch baselines.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Reiterate that decoupling angular signals via physical priors and geometric routing successfully overcomes the spectral analysis limitations of low-resolution sampling, establishing a new theoretical directive for future light field networks to rely on physical geometry rather than blind parameter tuning."